icisms that have been leveled against neo-Kantianism.Addressing both "commun-itarian" critics who argue that universalist conceptions of justice sever moral deliberation from community traditions, and feminist advocates of the "ethics of care" who stress the moral significance of caring for other individuals, Rehg shows that discourse ethics combines impartiality with solidarity. He provides the first systematic reconstruction of Habermas's theory and explores its relationship to the work of such contemporary philosophers as Charles Taylor. His book articulates a bold alternative to the split between the "right" and the "good" in moral theory and will greatly interest philosophers, social and legal scholars, and political theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthics, Moderny20th century. 0aHistoriography. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  acharles taylor.  acommun itarian.  acommunicative action.  acommunity traditions.  adiscourse ethics.  aethics of care.  aethics.  afeminism.  aimpartiality.  ajurgen habermas.  ajustice.  akant.  alegal studies.  amoral deliberation.  amoral theory.  amorality.  aneo kantian moral theory.  aneo kantianism.  aphilosophical debate.  aphilosophy of ethics.  aphilosophy of morality.  aphilosophy.  apolitical theory.  arule of law.  asocial sciences.  asocial theory.  asolidarity.  auniversalist conceptions of justice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020897140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919174?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919174423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919174/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University 